:1,"options":["Oestrogen and progesterone levels rise to maintain the endometrium","Prostaglandin production decreases in the endometrium","The functionalis layer becomes necrotic and is shed","The basalis layer undergoes complete degeneration","Matrix metalloproteinase activity decreases with progesterone withdrawal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the menstrual phase, falling progesterone levels trigger endometrial breakdown. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoestrogen and progesterone levels\u003C/strong\u003E actually fall, not rise, leading to withdrawal of endometrial support. \u003Cstrong\u003EProstaglandin production increases\u003C/strong\u003E, not decreases, causing uterine contractions that help expel menstrual tissue. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efunctionalis layer \u003C/strong\u003E(the outer layer of the endometrium) becomes necrotic and is shed, while the \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasalis layer\u003C/strong\u003E remains intact to regenerate the endometrium in the next cycle. \u003Cstrong\u003EMatrix metalloproteinase activity increases\u003C/strong\u003E with progesterone withdrawal, contributing to tissue breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Progesterone withdrawal triggers menstruation through increased matrix metalloproteinase activity and vasoconstriction","The functionalis layer of the endometrium is shed during menstruation due to hormone withdrawal","Prostaglandin production increases during menstruation, causing uterine contractions assisting in expulsion of menstrual tissue"],"references":["Hawkins SM, Matzuk MM. The menstrual cycle: basic biology. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2008;1135:10-8. doi: 10.1196/annals.1429.018. PMID: 18574203; PMCID: PMC2913133","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015).